@NODE "CLI" "Runing Adagis from the CLI"
@TOC "How it works"

@{b}Runing Adagis from the CLI@{ub}

You can run Adagis from the CLI. In this case Adagis WILL NOT open a GUI, as it's supposed that you will use Adagis through it's ARexx port.

As any MUI app, Adagis is a commodity, so you can quit using a program like 'Exchange', too.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "ARexx" "Adagis v4 ARexx interface"
@TOC "How it works"

@{b}Adagis ARexx interface@{ub}

Adagis 4 features an ARexx interface.
The port is 'ADAGIS.X', where X=1,2,3...

Currently, Adagis supports the following ARexx commands:

GET_OFFSET OFFSET

Gets an adage by it's offset. Of course, this function depends on the current AddOn, so will not always run.

GET_ORDINAL POSITION

Gets an adage by it's ordinal position in the file. Of course, this function depends on the current AddOn, so will not always run.

GET_RANDOM

Gets an adage randomly (The mode depends on the current AddOn).

CURRENT_OFFSET

Returns the current adage offset.

Adagis recognizes the standard MUI commands:

QUIT / FORCEQUIT

Quits Adagis.

HIDE

Iconifies Adagis.

SHOW

De-iconifies Adagis.
Note: SHOW and HIDE will make no effect if Adagis runs without GUI.

Please refer to MUI docs for more information about these standard commands.

I've included a couple of sample programs in the Rexx dir of the distribution. They are very simple.

Adagis_CLI.rexx:
This one expects Adagis to be running. Simply displays an adage in the shell.

Adagis_WB.rexx:
This one loads Adagis (if needed) and displays an adage in a window.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "AddOns" "Adagis v4's AddOns"
@TOC "How it works"

@{b}Adagis' AddOns@{ub}

Adagis v4 supports (and requires) the so-called AddOns.

An AddOn is a piece of code (a standard library) that is capable of reading cookie-files. Each AddOn reads an specific format.

The installation installs the 2 available AddOns, so you can change between them easily.

By now, only 2 AddOns are available, but more may come in the future. It really depends on the users (as usual).

These two AddOns are:

Adagis_adagis.addon:
This one allows Adagis to read it's own file format. It's not built-in because this would make Adagis' executable larger, and I find it unnecessary.
The default search mode is 'Offset'.

Adagis_IC.addon:
With this AddOn you can use IntuiCookie files with Adagis.
IntuiCookie is a great fortune cookie program by Christian Kemp.
All the formatting codes will be filtered. Only the '--' is left.
The AddOn use of course the ICookie Hash file, so accessing a given cookie is a lot faster with this format/AddOn than with the Adagis one.
The default search mode is 'Ordinal'. Actually, the 'Offset' mode is disabled for this AddOn.
Note that the hash-file MUST have the nameof the cookie file with the extension '.hash'.
Thanks to Christian Kemp for his help, and for letting me make this AddOn.

Some notes:

-Every file-format has its own 'Default' search mode. It's possible that, due to the format, not all the 'Search modes' that Adagis features will work on every AddOn.
By now, the 2 AddOns support all the search-modes.

-The AddOns can resport an error like 'Out of range'. This means that you have specified an adage that cannot be found in the cookie-file.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Tech" "Some tech stuff"
@TOC "MAIN"

@{b}Tech notes@{ub}

-Unlike previous Adagis versions (v1/v2), v4 doesn't hold the whole Adagis.data in the RAM. The obvious advantage is that with large cookie-files the RAM usage remains the same as when working with little  files. But the method Adagis uses has the disadvantage (?) that it can't know both the current cookie and the total number of cookies.
This only applies to Adagis file AddOn.

-When Adagis random-selects an adage, it has instant access to it, and it displays its offset (in bytes) in the file.

-If you want you can get an adage selecting its number, but then the access could be *slow*, as Adagis has no information about the positions of adages, and has to search in the file line by line.
This only applies to Adagis-file-format AddOn.

-You may notice that if you specify an offset, probably Adagis will not jump exactly to that offset. It jumps to the first cookie it finds after this offset.

-Yes, I have to admit that the timing code of Adagis v4 is very crap... This is why Adagis (still) sets its priority to -1. As soon as I learn how to deal with timer.device, Adagis will make use of it.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Usage" "Using Adagis"
@TOC "MAIN"

@{b}How to use the program@{ub}

Adagis v4 has two main MUI-pages.

@{u}Adagis:@{uu} Its (nearly) identical to the GUI of Adagis v2.x/v3.x.

Adagis selects an adage and displays it in the list. It then waits a time proportional to the number of lines of the adage and quits.

This page contains 3 buttons:

Freeze: Adagis will not quit until you press quit (the busy class in not shown when Adagis is freezed).
More: Adagis will choose and display a new adage.
Quit: Is obvious, no ?

The second page contains only the 'About' information of Adagis v4.

Most Adagis v4's features have been moved to menus:

@{u}Project:@{uu}
About Adagis: Obvious.
About AddOn: Displays some information about the AddOn that Adagis is using to interpret the data file.
Iconify: Obvious too.
Quit: ...

@{u}Miscellaneous:@{uu}
Analyze file: This function analyzes the whole data-file and displays some interesting (?) information about it.
Be warned that it can take some time.
Save adage: Saves the current adage in a file. An ASL requester will appear, so you can specify the file where you want to save the adage.
Copy to clip: Copies tge current cookie to the clipboard, so you can inmediatly paste it into your favourite text-editor by using the 'Paste' function.
Navigation: Opens the Navigation window.

@{u}Settings:@{uu}
MUI: Opens the MUIPrefs program for Adagis4.
AdagisPrefs: Runs 'AdagisPrefs'. See @{" AdagisPrefs " LINK "AdagisPrefs"}
Reload prefs: Closes Adagis window, rereads the configuration and opens it again.

The Navigation window contains 3 pages:

Ordinal: Allows you to search an adage by its ordinal position in the cookie-file. Note that -depending on the AddOn- this search-mode can take some time. Valid entries go from 0 to #Cookies-1.
Offset: Allows you to search an adage by its position in the cookie-file in bytes.
Navigation: Adagis remembers the cookies that you've seen since you started it. In this page you'll find a slider that allows you to 'navigate' through these cookies.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Adagis.data" "Adagis.data file"
@TOC "MAIN"

@{b}The Adagis.data file@{ub}

The Adagis.data file contains the adages.
It's a plain ASCII file, so you can edit it with your favourite text editor.

Its structure is very simple:

>>Adagis<<
#
Adage 1
#
Adage 2
#
Adage 3
#
.
.
.
#
Adage N


Each adage is preceeded by a '#'.

Please, don't play with the file, because you can easily hang Adagis.

Note:
This format is read/analyzed by the 'Adagis_adagis.addon'. If you plan to use another cookie-file-format (currently only IntuiCookie AddOn is available) refer to the docs of the program in question.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "AdagisPrefs" "Configuration"
@TOC "MAIN"

@{b}The AdagisPrefs program@{ub}

Adagis is a MUI program, so you can configure everything...

I recommend you to use large fonts in lists, 14 or 15 points, as they make adages more easy to read.

Internal Adagis' settings can be modified through AdagisPrefs. You can run it directly from the WB or by selecting the 'Settings/AdagisPrefs' menu (in this case, be sure that the 'ADAGISPREFS' tooltype is set).

AdagisPrefs is very easy to use. Only some notes:

-You MUST specify an AddOn.

-You MUST specify a cookie file.

-Don't play with Create/Don't create GUI. Running Adagis w/o a GUI is only usefull if you plan to use it through the ARexx port.

By now, Adagis don't react to a change in the config. This will probably change in a newer version of the program.
You can reread the configuration without having to quit Adagis using the menu 'Reload prefs'.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "History" "History"
@TOC "MAIN"

@{b}History@{ub}

v0.1...0.9:

       ßetaversions.

v1.0...1.8:

       Only few people saw them.
       Used the gadtools.library.

v2.1:

       First working MUI-version of Adagis.
       Uploaded to Aminet.
       Configurable via tooltypes.

v2.2:

       Internal changes.
       Never saw the light.
       Not uploaded to Aminet due to v3.

v3.0:

       Requires MUI 3.2+.
       Adagis.data not hold in RAM.
       Sample english cookie-file.
       Uploaded to Aminet.

v3.1:

       New AUTHOR tooltype
       New 'Jump to...' window
       Internal changes

v3.2:

       New ADAGISFILE tooltype
       New CLOSEWINS tooltype
       Adagis can save the current adage in a file
       New 'Navigation' window/feature
       Adagis' windows don't block Adagis' window
       Internal changes
       Some bugs removed

v3.2a:

       Not uploaded to the Aminet.
       Some minor changes (concerning to the GUI).

v4.0:

       New GUI, not build using MUIBuilder.
       New cool feature: AddOns.
       Adagis has now some ARexx commands.
       Adagis can be run from CLI (->NOGUI)
       Adagis list is now a Floattext object
       New AdagisPrefs program.

v4.0b:

       Some bugs corrected.
       Some internal changes.
       Parts of the code optimized.
       Little changes in distribution.

v4.1

       A couple of bugs removed
       New nice logo ! :-)
       New copy to clip function
       Better random # generator.

